<spring_boot_security_guide>
<title>SPRING BOOT SECURITY TESTING</title>

<critical>Spring Boot is the dominant Java web framework. Its convention-over-configuration approach can hide security issues. Testing must focus on Actuator endpoint exposure, SpEL injection, mass assignment via data binding, template injection, and Spring Security misconfigurations.</critical>

<scope>
- Actuator endpoint exposure
- Spring Expression Language (SpEL) injection
- Mass assignment via data binding
- Thymeleaf and other template injection
- Spring Security bypass
- Error page information disclosure
- Deserialization vulnerabilities
- Authentication and authorization flaws
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Discover Actuator endpoints and assess exposure.
2. Test for SpEL injection in dynamic expressions.
3. Probe data binding for mass assignment vulnerabilities.
4. Examine template rendering for injection opportunities.
5. Test Spring Security filters for bypass conditions.
</methodology>

